eased","1356–Female":"1356–Deceased","1447":"1447","1356":"1356","1378":"1378","1398":"1398","about 1356":"about 1356","1385":"1385","1352":"1352","1392":"1392","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud was born about 1356, in Montgomeryshire, Wales. She had at least 4 sons and 3 daughters with Gruffudd ap Ieuan."},"et":{"about 1356–Deceased":"umbes 1356–Surnud","1352–Male":"1352–Surnud","1378–Male":"1378–Surnud","1385–1447":"1385–1447","1392–1447":"1392–1447","1398–Male":"1398–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1356–Female":"1356–Surnud","1447":"1447","1356":"1356","1378":"1378","1398":"1398","about 1356":"umbes 1356","1385":"1385","1352":"1352","1392":"1392","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1356–Deceased":"noin 1356–Kuollut","1352–Male":"1352–Kuollut","1378–Male":"1378–Kuollut",